<Layout title="Horsepower vs Kilowatts: Car Power Explained" description="Convert between horsepower and kilowatts for car engines. Understand what these power units mean and why different countries use different measurements." keywords="horsepower to kilowatts, hp vs kW, car power, engine power, horsepower explained, kilowatt conversion, motor power units">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Power</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Horsepower vs Kilowatts: Car Power Explained</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 13, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>When comparing cars, Americans talk horsepower while Europeans and Australians use kilowatts. Electric vehicles have made this even more confusing with their instant torque and different performance characteristics. Here is what these units mean and how to compare them.</p>

      <h2>The Conversion</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 horsepower (hp) = 0.7457 kilowatts (kW)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 mt-1">1 kilowatt (kW) = 1.341 horsepower (hp)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Quick estimate: hp × 0.75 = kW (or kW × 1.34 = hp)</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Common Car Power Outputs Converted</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>100 hp = 75 kW (small city car)</li>
        <li>150 hp = 112 kW (average family car)</li>
        <li>200 hp = 149 kW (sporty hatchback)</li>
        <li>300 hp = 224 kW (performance sedan)</li>
        <li>400 hp = 298 kW (sports car)</li>
        <li>500 hp = 373 kW (muscle car / performance EV)</li>
        <li>1,000 hp = 746 kW (hypercar)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What is a Horsepower?</h2>
      <p>James Watt coined the term in the 1780s to sell steam engines. He calculated that a typical draft horse could do 33,000 foot-pounds of work per minute and defined one horsepower as that rate. Despite the name, a real horse can actually produce about 15 hp in short bursts.</p>

      <h2>Types of Horsepower</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mechanical/Imperial hp:</strong> 745.7 watts (used in US/UK)</li>
        <li><strong>Metric hp (PS/CV):</strong> 735.5 watts (used in Germany/France — slightly smaller)</li>
        <li><strong>Brake hp (bhp):</strong> Measured at the engine output shaft (used in UK car reviews)</li>
        <li><strong>Wheel hp (whp):</strong> Measured at the wheels (15-20% less than bhp due to drivetrain losses)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why Electric Cars Changed the Conversation</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>EVs are naturally specified in kW since they use electric motors</li>
        <li>A Tesla Model 3 Performance: 340 kW (456 hp)</li>
        <li>EV power is available instantly (peak torque from 0 rpm) unlike combustion engines</li>
        <li>This makes raw power numbers less comparable between EVs and petrol cars for acceleration</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Power vs Torque</h2>
      <p>Power (hp/kW) determines top speed. Torque (Nm/lb-ft) determines acceleration feel. A diesel truck might have huge torque but modest horsepower, while a sports car has high horsepower but less torque. For daily driving, torque at low revs matters more than peak power.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/power" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Power Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/power" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
